## Who would benefit from your app playground and how?
*(200 words max)*

Anyone who spends time in areas with unreliable connectivity. Hikers, campers, rural communities, disaster-affected families, travellers in remote regions. In India alone, the Western Ghats, the Himalayas, and the Northeast see hundreds of emergencies every year where people have smartphones but no signal.

The first group is people facing an active emergency. The triage system asks branching questions like a first responder would and narrows 505 techniques to the right one in three taps. A parent whose child is choking doesn't need to know the Heimlich manoeuvre exists. They tap "I'm Hurt," answer two questions, and the app tells them what to do.

Second, people who want to be prepared. The guide covers 10 domains from fire-starting to shelter construction for anyone planning backcountry travel.

Third, communities in disaster-prone regions. Kerala floods, Wayanad landslides, the 2015 Chennai floods that submerged the city I grew up in. These events cut connectivity for days. An offline app with medically accurate first aid, emergency signalling tools like the SOS flashlight and siren, and a built-in compass becomes genuinely useful on a device everyone already owns.

No account needed. No internet needed. Works instantly.

