## How did accessibility factor into your design process?
*(200 words max)*

Accessibility isn't a bonus feature for Revive—it's the entire point. People using this app are likely panicking, in the dark, or physically injured. That reality shaped every line of code.

I built a completely hands-free voice control engine using SFSpeechRecognizer and AVSpeechSynthesizer. If someone is applying pressure to a wound or holding a splint, they can just say "next step" or "repeat" without ever touching their screen. 

The UI itself is heavily optimized for stress. Everything is dark-mode only—not for aesthetics, but to preserve night vision and save battery life when power grids are down. The triage buttons are massive (56pt minimum) high-contrast tap targets that are impossible to miss even if your hands are shaking. Under the hood, every single interactive element has custom accessibilityLabel handling, and decorative UI is stripped out with accessibilityHidden(true) so VoiceOver users get zero noise. 

In a real emergency—like hiding under a car seat where FaceID cannot see you—you can simply whisper *"Hey Siri, start siren on Revive"* to instantly trigger the 120dB alarm. I specifically configured the AppIntent with `openAppWhenRun = false` so Siri executes it instantly in the background without forcing the user to unlock their phone.

